y and all directories below it. Find is recursive by nature and will search the entire file structure if allowed.\r\n\r\nThe third part of this command is the \"-name\" switch. This basically tells the server that you\'re looking for a file by name. So, what if we don\'t know the whole file name or don\'t know what type of file it is? Perhaps we just know that the word \"declare\" is somewhere in the file? Can the find command still help us? Absolutely! To find a file using only part of the file name, try the following:\r\n\r\nfind ./ -name \"*declare*\"\r\n\r\nA * in Linux acts as a wildcard allowing you to tell the find command \"Grab everything with declare in the middle of it, and ignore text on either side\".\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Finding a file by name','','publish','closed','open','','using-the-find-command-in-linux','','','2012-10-28 00:19:16','2012-10-28 00:19:16','',0,'http://oakwoodsystems.net/?p=131',0,'post','',0),(132,1,'2012-08-25 15:24:35','2012-08-25 15:24:35','The find command is probably the easiest way to locate a file, folder, or group of both, on a linux server. Let\'s walk through a few uses of the find command.\n\n<strong>Finding a file by name</strong>\n\nIn this example we\'re going to assume that we\'re looking for a single file labeled declaration.txt that\'s somewhere in the current directory. The command to find it would be as follows.\n\nfind ./ -name \"declaration.txt\"\n\nThe beginning of the command is the \"find\" statement telling the server that you\'re looking for a file or folder. The second part of this statement \"./\" tells the server to look in the current directory and all directories below it. Find is recursive by nature and will search the entire file structure if allowed.\n\nThe third part of this command is the \"-name\" switch. This basically tells the server that you\'re looking for a file by name. So, what if we don\'t know the whole file name or don\'t know what type of file it is? Perhaps we 