     76124          14%  /boot\r\ntmpfs                                                         16375892    0                 16375892   0%   /dev/shm\r\n[root@localhost ~]#\r\n\r\nOK. So, we know that we\'ve got 98% disk space used in one of our partitions but we don\'t have a lot of information on where that space is being used. That\'s where the du command comes in handy. Going to the server root(cd /) enter the following command.\r\n\r\ndu --max-depth 1 -h\r\n\r\nLet me break the command down a bit. The \"du\" command by itself will display the directory sizes in Kilobytes of your present directory and every directory below it making it somewhat illegible. You\'re dealing with too much data at this point. The --max-depth 1 tells the server that you only want to see the sizes of directories in your present directory. -h, as with most commands, makes the output more user friendly by giving you sizes in Megabytes of Gigabytes. From here, you can go down through your file structure and locate your problem directory, script, or user.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Dealing with disk space overuse in CentOS','','publish','closed','closed','','230','','','2012-10-28 20:06:35','2012-10-28 20:06:35','',0,'http://oakwoodsystems.net/?p=230',0,'post','',0),(231,2,'2012-10-28 18:24:21','2012-10-28 18:24:21','One problem every admin in the world will eventually have to deal with is your server\'s disk filling up. This is often caused by automated backups, excessive error logs, and poorly written cron jobs. If you\'re administering a shared server this becomes even more of an issue as most hosting control panels and Linux distros don\'t have a built in way of limiting your users disk space usage.\n\nSo, first off, how do we tell how much of our disk space we\'re actually using? Fortunately the df command gives us just that. Running the command, you should see something like this\n\n[root@localhost ~]# df\nFilesystem                                                1K