erverName www.webadmin.com\r\n     ServerAlias webadmin.com\r\n     SuexecUserGroup webadmin webadmin\r\n\r\n     RewriteEngine on\r\n        \r\n</VirtualHost>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','Building a CentOS Web Server Part 1','','trash','closed','closed','','building-a-centos-web-server-part-1','','','2012-12-10 02:32:30','2012-12-10 02:32:30','',0,'http://oakwoodsystems.net/?p=236',0,'post','',0),(237,1,'2012-10-30 00:26:51','2012-10-30 00:26:51','In this tutorial I\'d like to walk you through building a basic CentOS web server from scratch. This tutorial assumes that you\'re using CentOS 6.x and that you\'re intending to set up your server on the command line though most of it will work with other CentOS versions. I\'m also assuming that you\'ve already configured your network interfaces and that you\'ve got full root access on the system. \n\nSo, without further ado, let\'s begin!\n\nStep 1: Installing And Configuring Apache\n\nInstalling Apache is fairly simple and can be done with the yum command on CentOS. If yum fails, go to Google and search \"Configuring yum on CentOS\" or something similar. To install Apache, run the following:\n\nyum -y install httpd\n\nAfter this you\'ll need to create a user, webadmin for this example, to run your website as and assign that user a password.\n\nuseradd webadmin\npasswd webadmin\n\nNow you\'ll need to configure the Apache httpd.conf. This is the file that basically designates what files will be available to the web, what user to run them as, where to store log files, and a host of other information. In most cases the httpd.conf file will be in /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf. I\'ll show you a copy of our very simplified httpd.conf file below and we\'ll go over it afterwards.\n\n<VirtualHost *:80>\n     ServerAdmin engineering@worldspice.net\n     DocumentRoot /home/webadmin\n     ServerName www.webadmin.\n     ServerAlias \n     SuexecUserGroup webadmin webadmin\n\n\n        RewriteEngine on\n        #RewriteCond %{REMOTE_HOST} !^66\\.190\\.122\\.94\n        #RewriteRule ^(.*)$ http://www.compperformancegroupstores.com/maintenance.html\n\n</VirtualHost>\n\n\n\n\n\n','Building a CentOS Web Server Part 1','','inherit','closed','closed','','236-revision','','','2012-10-30 00:26:51','2012-10-30 00:26:51','',236,'http://oakwoodsystems.net/uncategorized/236-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(240,1,'2012-12-01 15:16:07','2012-12-01 15:16:07','<h2>Oakwood Systems will never sell, distribute, reveal, or make available of any customer information. We support the work of the anti-spam organizations. If there is ever a need to contact you in regards to your specific account and service, we will only contact you though email. Oakwood Systems reserves the right to make any reasonable adjustments to our terms of service at anytime. Clients agree to abide by any additions or adjustments to our terms of service, as they are available to be viewed by anyone at anytime.</h2>\n<h3>Satisfaction Guaranteed</h3>\nFor Shared and Reseller Accounts ONLY: If for any legitimate reason you are unsatisfied with the services received from Simple Helix Hosting during the first 30 days, you may request to discontinue our services and receive your full refund by emailing us at <a href=\"mailto: sales@simplehelix.com\">sales@simplehelix.com</a>. You must provide us with a reason as to why you are choosing to cancel our services. We are the sole arbiter in determining the validity of your reason. If all possible steps were taken on your side and on ours to correct the situation a full refund will be issued. This guarantee only applies to the first 30 days and does not apply to any accounts other than shared and reseller.\n<h3>Domain Names and Domain Transfers</h3>\nAs part of our \"ethical hosting guidelines\", Oakwood Systems Hosting will take necessary steps to register domain names on behalf of the client when requested. However, clients are responsible for renewing their domain names. Oakwood Systems Hosting does not take re