e file that basically designates what files will be available to the web, what user to run them as, where to store log files, and a host of other information. In most cases the httpd.conf file will be in /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf. I\'ll show you a copy of our very simplified httpd.conf file below and we\'ll go over it afterwards.\r\n\r\n<VirtualHost *:80>\r\n     DocumentRoot /home/webadmin/public_html\r\n     ServerName www.webadmin.com\r\n     ServerAlias webadmin.com\r\n     SuexecUserGroup webadmin webadmin\r\n\r\n     RewriteEngine on\r\n        \r\n</VirtualHost>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','Building a CentOS Web Server Part 1','','inherit','closed','closed','','236-revision-2','','','2012-10-30 00:27:41','2012-10-30 00:27:41','',236,'http://oakwoodsystems.net/uncategorized/236-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(287,2,'2012-12-10 21:34:57','2012-12-10 21:34:57','To set file permissions in your Magento store, cd to your Magento root and enter the following commands.\r\n<pre>find ./ -type f -exec chmod 0644 {} \\;\r\nfind ./ -type d -exec chmod 0755 {} \\;</pre>\r\n<pre>chmod -R 0777 ./var ./media</pre>','Setting File Permissions in Magento','','publish','closed','closed','','setting-file-permissions-in-magento','','','2012-12-10 21:34:57','2012-12-10 21:34:57','',0,'http://oakwoodsystems.net/?p=287',0,'post','',0),(288,2,'2012-12-10 21:34:38','2012-12-10 21:34:38','To set file permissions in your Magento store, cd to your Magento root and enter the following commands.\n<pre>find ./ -type f -exec chmod 0644 {} \\;\nfind ./ -type d -exec chmod 0755 {} \\;</pre>\n<pre>chmod -R 0777</pre>','Setting File Permissions in Magento','','inherit','closed','closed','','287-revision','','','2012-12-10 21:34:38','2012-12-10 21:34:38','',287,'http://oakwoodsystems.net/uncategorized/287-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(289,1,'2012-12-12 18:08:34','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Order','','draft','closed','closed','','','','','2012-12-12 18:08:34','2012-12-12 18:08:34','',0,'http://oakwood